faqQuestion: When am I eligible to participate in the 401(k) plan?
faqAnswer: You are eligible to participate in the 401(k) plan immediately. Generally, summer interns and temporary colleagues are not eligible.

faqQuestion: How do I enroll in the 401(k) plan?
faqAnswer: You can enroll any time. You can also call 1.555.555.5555, 24 hours a day, seven days a week, to enroll or you may speak with a Customer Service Representative by selecting zero. Customer Service Representatives are available Monday through Friday from 8:00 a.m. to 8:00 p.m. (ET)
faqDescription: How do I enroll in the 401(k) plan?

faqQuestion: How much can I contribute to my 401(k) plan?
faqAnswer: You decide the amount you want to contribute – from 1 percent to 50 percent of your pay (including base, overtime and incentive) – on a pre-tax basis or on a post-tax basis as Roth contributions. Under IRS regulations, your pre-tax and Roth combined are limited to $18,000 in 2016. You are also eligible to make "catch-up" contributions if you will be at least age 50 in the calendar year and expect to reach IRS limits. IRS allows catch-up contributions up to $6,000 in 2016.
faqDescription: How much can I contribute to my 401(k) plan?

faqQuestion: When does my 401(k) plan balance become vested?
faqAnswer: Your right to the balance in your 401(k) plan account is called vesting. You are always 100 percent vested in your own contributions and the earnings on your contributions. You are 100 percent vested in your entire account balance – including the dollar for dollar matching contributions up to 6 percent of pay immediately.
faqDescription: When does my 401(k) plan balance become vested?

faqQuestion: Who is eligible for the additional non-elective contribution?
faqAnswer:
If you are colleague not participating in the Pension Plan (hired after January 1, 2009, you will receive a three percent matching contribution to your 401(k) account, (whether or not you are contributing). You will be vested in the non-elective contribution once you complete three years of service.

faqQuestion: Can I get a loan or make a withdrawal from my 401(k) account?
faqAnswer: While employed, you will have access to your money through loans and limited withdrawals. You may request a loan or withdrawal by calling 1.866.472.8234. However, because the plan is designed for long-term savings, certain restrictions apply.

faqQuestion: Is financial help available for adoption proceedings?
faqAnswer: Yes. Financial assistance is provided to full-time associates who are going through domestic or international adoption proceedings.

faqQuestion: How much will be paid toward adoption expenses?
faqAnswer: Eligible adoption expenses will be covered up to the maximum amount (currently $11,650) allowed under IRS regulations. Associates who are in the adoption process are also eligible for a $10,000 five-year forgivable subsidy in addition to the reimbursement amount.

Eligible expenses include licensed adoption agency fees, legal and court costs, medical expenses for the birth mother, medical expenses of the child before adoption and post-adoption counseling for the child.

faqQuestion: How do I apply for adoption assistance?
faqAnswer: To apply for adoption assistance you need to complete an Adoption Assistance Reimbursement Form available from the Human Resources Service Center and submit it along with itemized bills. The HR Service Center may request additional documentation of your expenses. You must request reimbursement within 90 days of incurring the expense. Reimbursements will be made directly to you.

faqQuestion: When can I enroll in benefits?
faqAnswer: You can enroll in or make changes to your benefits each year during annual enrollment; you can change your benefits during the year only when you have a qualified status change. Also, you must re-certify and re-enroll your dependents who are full-time students age 19 or older.
faqDescription: When can I enroll in benefits?

faqQuestion: How do I know whether I am a full-time associate or a part- time associate?
faqAnswer:
-Full-time associates are scheduled to work 30 hours or more each week. 
-Part-time associates are scheduled to work less than 30 hours each week

faqQuestion: How can I change my benefit elections during the year?
faqAnswer: The benefit elections you make during annual enrollment or as a new hire remain in effect for the entire year unless you experience a qualified status change. According to the IRS, a qualified work or family status change includes birth, adoption, marriage, divorce, death, a change in your employment status or your spouse’s, a change in your dependent’s eligibility for his or her employer’s plans, or becoming eligible for Medicare or Medicaid. In any of these cases, you have the ability to make changes to your benefits. The change must be consistent with your change in status.
